`,l.jsxs(r.p,{children:["For much of the 2000s and early 2010s, many sites followed a familiar pattern: the server rendered HTML, the browser displayed it, and JavaScript improved interactivity where needed. ",l.jsx(r.strong,{children:"jQuery"})," made that layer approachable across inconsistent browsers. ",l.jsx(r.strong,{children:"WordPress"}),", ",l.jsx(r.strong,{children:"Drupal"}),", and similar CMS platforms made publishing fast for millions of sites. That stack still works for a large share of the web today."]}),`
`,l.jsxs(r.p,{children:["What changed was ",l.jsx(r.strong,{children:"user expectations"}),". Search-as-you-type, live dashboards, collaborative editing, and mobile apps raised the bar for interactivity. Teams building long-lived ",l.jsx(r.strong,{children:"applications"})," — not only articles and brochures — often adopted component-based JavaScript frameworks. ",l.jsx(r.strong,{children:"React"})," became one of the most widely used options for that job. ",l.jsx(r.strong,{children:"React Native"})," extended a similar component model to iOS and Android."]}),`
`,l.jsx(r.p,{children:"This article discusses those shifts in neutral terms. jQuery, WordPress, and React solve overlapping but not identical problems. Preferences here reflect the author's experience; your stack should match your product, team skills, and maintenance horizon."}),`
`,l.jsx(r.h2,{children:"What jQuery did well — and where larger apps strained"}),`
`,l.jsxs(r.p,{children:[l.jsx(r.a,{href:"https://jquery.com/",children:"jQuery"})," remains maintained and appropriate for many tasks. It unified DOM APIs, simplified events and AJAX, and helped a generation of developers ship interactivity quickly. For small enhancements on server-rendered pages, it is still a reasonable choice."]}),`
`,l.jsxs(r.p,{children:["Difficulties tended to appear as ",l.jsx(r.strong,{children:"application complexity"}),' grew. Imperative DOM updates — select an element, mutate it, bind another handler — can scatter state across the page. In large codebases, answering "what is on screen?" may require tracing selectors instead of reading a single state model. That pain point motivated declarative libraries, including React, Vue, and others — not a failure of jQuery itself, but a different scale of problem.']}),`
`,l.jsxs("table",{children:[l.jsx("thead",{children:l.jsxs("tr",{children:[l.jsx("th",{children:"Approach"}),l.jsx("th",{children:"Mental model"}),l.jsx("th",{children:"Often strong for"}),l.jsx("th",{children:"Common scaling challenges"})]})}),l.jsxs("tbody",{children:[l.jsxs("tr",{children:[l.jsx("td",{children:"jQuery"}),l.jsx("td",{children:"Enhance the DOM in place"}),l.jsx("td",{children:"Progressive enhancement, legacy pages"}),l.jsx("td",{children:"State spread across imperative updates"})]}),l.jsxs("tr",{children:[l.jsx("td",{children:"Backbone / Knockout"}),l.jsx("td",{children:"Models with bindings"}),l.jsx("td",{children:"Structured medium-sized apps (historical)"}),l.jsx("td",{children:"Boilerplate and binding complexity at scale"})]}),l.jsxs("tr",{children:[l.jsx("td",{children:"AngularJS (1.x)"}),l.jsx("td",{children:"Full framework in the page"}),l.jsx("td",{children:"Enterprise CRUD (historical)"}),l.jsx("td",{children:"Large-app performance and migration paths"})]}),l.jsxs("tr",{children:[l.jsx("td",{children:"React"}),l.jsx("td",{children:"UI as a function of state"}),l.jsx("td",{children:"Component-driven product UIs"}),l.jsx("td",{children:"Tooling choices and ecosystem breadth"})]})]})]}),`
`,l.jsx(r.p,{children:"React's declarative model asks: given this state, what should render? That can simplify reviews, tests, and refactors when many people touch the same UI — one reason product teams adopted it, alongside alternatives such as Vue and Angular."}),`
`,l.jsx(r.h2,{children:"WordPress and CMS platforms: different layer, different strength"}),`
